{
  "texts": [
    "While the findings demonstrate that models exhibit context-dependent disclosure patterns that create the preconditions for a Reverse Gell-Mann Amnesia effect, this research has not observed users being misled.",
    "The claim that users would overgeneralize trust based on observing appropriate disclosure in some domains remains a plausible hypothesis rather than an empirically demonstrated user behavior.",
    "Controlled user studies would be needed to confirm whether users exhibit this pattern of trust miscalibration and whether the observed model behavior translates into the predicted user harms.Evaluation was restricted to open-weight models, which was necessary to measure parameter count and test model size as a predictor.",
    "Whether similar patterns exist among frontier closedsource models requires direct empirical testing.",
    "The shared training paradigm of transformer-based models with RLHF and safety fine-tuning makes similar context-dependence plausible, though exact performance may differ.GPT-OSS-120B served as both a subject model and the evaluating judge, introducing potential self-preference bias."
  ]
}